Soaked in corruption
My friend Boris was leaving my house, drunk.
I therefore suggested that he shouldn't drive.
He asked me why.
“You've been drinking,” I said, “aren't you afraid of the police?”
Boris replied: "No, I have a document featuring Benjamin Franklin, it always comes in handy."
He showed me his driver's license with a $100 bill slipped next to it.
Obviously, I knew that the police take bribes, but I was worried that Boris might encounter an honest officer.
"Impossible," said Boris, "to get into the traffic police force, you have to buy your boss's silence."
If you don't take a bribe, how can you buy your boss's silence?
Half of the drivers in Moscow use illegally purchased driver's licenses.
Idiots who try to do things by the book drown in bureaucratic hassles.
By paying $100, you can drive around the city without brakes!
Corruption and embezzlement have always existed in Russia, before and after Lenin's October Revolution.
But never at the record levels we see today.
Everyone accepts bribes, everywhere and for everything.
The only ones who don't accept them are those to whom no one offers them, according to Boris.
Corruption thrives in most institutions, and the fight against corruption always ends in a catastrophe or abandonment.
The police, prosecutors, customs officers, and even the Kremlin: no one, nowhere is immune.
Recently, I was visiting a dacha village in one of the most beautiful suburbs of Moscow.
It was a lush but similar place to the gulag, with its high-security fences and guards.
Looking at the pretentious houses decorated with such little taste, I wondered who owned them and heard myself answer that one belonged to an assistant mayor of Moscow, another to a famous singer, and another to the son of Moscow's prosecutor.
But the most attractive property belonged to a modest tax office employee.
Corruption now represents a more serious threat to Russia than the Chechen war.
In fact, the Chechen war would not have lasted as long if it had not been conducted by corrupt generals, officers, civil servants, and police officers who sell weapons and supplies to the rebels.
The Russian television recently showed a bus shuttling between Grozny and Moscow, the same bus that brought to Moscow the 120 kilograms of explosives used for the siege of the Dubrovka theater, where so many victims perished during the assault intended to free the hostages.
A passenger on the bus covered the explosives with a cloth soaked in acid to prevent the dogs of the customs officers from detecting them.
A very unnecessary precaution.
No one controls the buses anymore today.
The driver, who did not know what he was transporting, said he was stopped 50 times along his route, and always for the same reason.
A policeman would come to him asking, "Do you know the price?" and the driver would reply, "Of course, I know it," paying the bribe before leaving.
Without a bribe, the bus would have been delayed for hours at each stop, or even days for the entire trip.
The war against Chechnya continues endlessly not only because Chechen rebels have allies in Al Qaïda and all "terrorist international" groups, but also because Russian corruption is their ally.
The police, the army, civilians who take bribes, and thieves—who first tax Chechen civilians or simply steal their belongings—sell weapons and explosives to terrorists, provide maps indicating where landmines are, and supply rebels with fake documents.
In May of this year, during the Kaspiisk explosions, terrorists used weapons purchased from Russian army officers.
The rebels have modern weapons.
Where do they come from?
In the mountains where the rebels hide, there are no gunshops.
But the 80,000 Russian soldiers fighting the rebels do have ammunition stocks, from which the weapons are stolen and sold.
And not only weapons: some young officers sell their own men into slavery.
Russian corruption has reached catastrophic levels, yet no fight has been launched against this plague.
Should corruption be punished more severely?
This would only raise the cost of corruption.
The harsher the punishment, the more one will have to pay to avoid it.
No official wants to fight corruption because they are themselves corrupt.
Thus, those called « the simple people » regard this phenomenon with benevolence.
They say of their mayor « of course he steals, but look at all he has done for the city! »
Ordinary people also do not like honest workers.
Why?
A train ticket costs 100 rubles, but by paying a small bribe, one can travel for 50 rubles.
The traveler and the conductor both benefit from this system.
An honest old grandmother once told me that she had bought a ticket and tried to board the train.
The conductor stopped her, telling her that passengers with a ticket were not allowed on the train!
For millions of Russians, corruption is a normal way of life.
If you don't want your son called up for military service, buy an army clerk and he will strike your son's name off the list, or bribe a doctor to declare him unfit for any military activity.
You can enter any university for a certain price, regardless of your references and diplomas.
You can drive drunk, speed, and ignore red lights, as long as Ben Franklin is there to offer himself to the police.
Alexander Menchikov, the minister of Peter the Great, understood the impossibility of winning the fight against corruption.
When Tsar Peter, disgusted by the corruption in Russia, decided to hang his corrupt officials, Menchikov replied: "Your Majesty, you risk losing all your subjects."
Since then, the situation has worsened.
Eliminating corruption could leave the state without citizens, but if we do not stop the spread of corruption, citizens will soon be left without a state.
